4.32/5  rDev -3.6%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5Pours with little visible carbonation. Tiny amount of brown head. The legs on the glass look kind of gritty, which I've found is often the sign of an overly sugary beer (although I know that not true here). It looks more like a bourbon-barrel-aged stout.
The smell is complex but balanced. There is a load of chocolate, cinnamon, and chiles, with hints of vanilla, oak, and fresh black coffee. It's sweet, spicy, and charred -- all well balanced. As it warms, a subtle earthiness also appears.
The taste follows the smell, but with a lot more chocolate upfront, and noticeable slight tingle from the chiles at the end. The coffee is present but subtle, not assertive like it would be in a full-blown coffee stout like Founders Breakfast Stout. The cinnamon and chili spice lingers at the finish, but it never builds up to a burn. The first few sips had a strange, metallic tinge, but that faded quickly.
It has a nice, soft, round feel, almost like an oatmeal stout. It look a little flat when poured, but, paradoxically, it's light on the tongue.
Overall: one of my all-time favorite non-barrel-aged stouts. With so many adjuncts, it could have become a confusing mess, but Prairie balanced everything beautifully. I would drink this beer every day if I could. 1,261 charactersccg, Dec 02, 2015
