4.61/5  rDev +2.9%look: 4.25 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Thanks to Alice in OK for finding this for me in Durant. Bottle indicates 13% abv. Second try, first review.
Stout glass pour: Jet black, and while I'm missing much head, the lacing ring is a darker rust color than I've ever seen before. 4
Smells fantastic enough. Chocolate nibs, freshly ground coffee, hints of licorice and the chile pepper. 
This is a bomb alright. Big hits of coffee and a bitter burning, and a slick, oily mouthfeel. Whether it's THE bomb, I remain reserved (THE as in at least my top 3 of the style). 
Chocolate flavor hits up front and I notice it the longer it sits. After awhile this reminds me of a regular breakfast stout as far as coffee goodness, but stronger with a chile spice pop, a pop that has distinct character. Powdery chocolatey chewy mouthfeel. Well rounded all-in-all. While normally chile in beer would be a drawback for my tastes, this is done right. I still prefer a sweet rounded stout as opposed to a sharper spicy one, however I think with this creation, most anyone would find something to enjoy about it. What did work with this the first time was some ice cream (Great beer float material. Vanilla I hear is recommended, although I did well with Guinness gelato (yes, the beer)). 
This tasting, however, is with no paired food. Just sipping this on a Texas night with temps headed down to 18F. Not much a better choice. 1,369 charactersTBoneJones, Jan 08, 2015
