4.75/5  rDev +6%Janis_Hoplin, Nov 22, 2013
5/5  rDev +11.6%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5I went on a beer quest with my brother in law when we were both in California, Santa Rosa area, to find this beverage specifically. I hadn't heard of it before since I don't really have my ear to the pulse of the beer scene or whatever but his description was enough to pique my interest. As Imperial Stouts are my undisputed favorite style of beer, I knew I had to try it if I had the chance. We ended up buying the last two bottles in all of Santa Rosa (supposedly) and at $10 for 12oz (I was expecting 750ml when they told me the price) I was hoping this would be worth the cost. AND IT WAS.
Appearance: black as night, 100% opaque, poured aggressively to get a good head but even with the bottle more than a foot above the glass nothing happened until a couple seconds after the pour. Absolutely the thickest beer I've ever seen. Like, I started raising the bottle as I poured and it just looked like it was flat, then sloooowwly the the head formed after the bottle was empty and I realized that I was seeing something special. And I might as well throw the term "khaki-colored" in there because apparently you are required by law to say that about stouts. It looked like pants.
Smell: It was a couple months ago so I honestly don't remember this aspect too well, really to me it's not an important part of a good beer--more of a preview of what's to come. Seriously, are you going to find a great-tasting beer that smells weird and mark it down because of that? 
Mouthfeel: Just like the appearance, it was unspeakably thick, coated the tongue just like it should for a massive imperial stout. The 12oz bottle was small but in retrospect it's a good thing because if this was in a bomber I probably wouldn't have enjoyed it by the end. It's that hearty.
Taste: Literally the best tasting beer I have ever consumed. It's my first review but far from my first beer. Really I chose this as my first review because I have such strong feelings about it. Everything advertised on the label is in here and all in perfect balance: coffee, chocolate, a hint of vanilla, and just enough chili peppers to gradually increase the heat on the fade as you work your way through the bottle. On the first couple of sips I was disappointed at the lack of pepper, but it builds so subtly and gradually that it doesn't start to hit you until you're about halfway done. By the time the bottle was sadly gone I still had the tasteful burn to remind me of what had been. The "roastiness" of a stout and the pepper heat are such a perfect match, I can't believe this flavor combination isn't more popular. And 14% ABV are you kidding me? I can handle an alcohol taste just fine, but there is almost none to speak of in this brew, and it's the strongest percentage-wise that I've ever had. The best way to describe it is to say that it's an experience you will never forget. 
Actually, if you're reading this review and haven't had it yet, then you shouldn't get your hopes up because it was only brewed once. Why do breweries do that? If this was year-round I would have given them hundreds of dollars by now. Oh well, thanks for the memories!!! 3,132 characterskrustster, Nov 22, 2013
5/5  rDev +11.6%krl2112, Nov 22, 2013
4.4/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4Consumed on tap at Mikkeller Bar SF. Very excited about trying this - I'm glad that the local distro gets this in quite often. Poured into a 20cl wine tulip glass. Just the right amount, if you ask me.
Pours a ridiculously blackened color - dark all the way, with some light brown against the light, but no way in hell is anything else going to go through this thing. Contains an off-khaki head, with some (albeit forced) carbonation streaking upwards against the sides of the glass. As the head recedes into a bit of a ring, it really looks like some freshly brewed espresso... Freshly brewed with chocolate and chili extract, that is, as the thickness is immediately apparent. As far as serious dessert beers go, this is top of the line eye candy in terms of presentation.
Wow! Tons of roasted notes, sweetened spices, and some fruitiness immediately hit the palate on this one. The coffee bitterness is extremely apparent at the front, and as someone who's worked in coffee shops before, this smells exactly like the same pungent, grainy characteristic of coffee beans as they are being ground right before your eyes. The chilies are there, but it's subtle - green pepper and white pepper notes, which soon meld with the roasted chocolate character, as well as a little bit of cinnamon, vanilla, and even a bit of maple syrup. Slight dark fruits, ranging from raisins to figs, but the highlight is the roasted flavor, and it really works well here. Best yet, the alcohol is meticulously masked - no burn, or anything. The sugars are covering it up, and yet, it contains all of the roasted and earthy flavors I prefer in an imperial stout. Win.
The flavor is more of the same, but it's definitely not as decadent as I expected this to be. Rather, it turns out to be a disgustingly easy beer to down, as it contains none of the syrupy, sweetened, or bold flavors that these kinds of beers usually drink. How is this possible? At first, it's awash with notes of roasted coffee beans and cocoa nibs, which soon meld into a brief sweetness cut with vanilla, nutmeg, and caramel. The raisin notes at the finish are delightful, but things get rather interesting once the pepper kicks in, as it adds a spicy kick to it - in a way, pretty much the same sensation as adding chili powder to a high quality hot cocoa beverage. The finish is cut mostly with a roasted grainy bitterness, which makes this easily drinkable. And, 14% ABV?? You're joking, right? This drinks like a beer that's half as strong. More importantly, the carbonation is probably the star of the show, in certain respects. It's just right, to the point where this neither too thick or thin, but rather just right so that it makes this an easy going experience, which is something I'd hardly say ever for a 28 proof beer.
I suppose the hype on this is well deserved, but don't think that I'd want more than 6oz at a time of this thing. It's delicious, and extremely well made to the point of hiding its true decadence and aggressive character. For its low price per bottle ($10, for what it is), this is something that I could buy regularly if I wanted something easy-drinking and wonderfully flavorful after dinner. To me, it reaches the heights that I like over-the-top imperial stouts to be - any further, however, is definitely pushing it. 3,308 charactersmagictacosinus, Nov 21, 2013
