4.5/5  rDev +0.4%imfrommichigan, Oct 17, 2013
4.36/5  rDev -2.7%look: 4.25 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 3.5 |  overall: 4.25Next great brewery to come to Indiana: Prairie. We Hoosiers have truly been blessed by the beer gods. Cheers!
A: A deep, impenetrable black body pours syrupy from the bottle; a half-inch head of dark brown fizz appears above, shining slick and iridescent in the light. Minimal lacing.
S: No mistaking the “wow” factor here – the aromas here are robust and phenomenally intoxicating. Centers around a bold cascade of fresh-ground coffee, bittersweet European chocolate, warm maple syrup, and toasted marshmallow; chili powder and bourbon barrel add a spicy note to it. It’s all rich and impossibly deep, a nose so dark and alluring you can’t help falling into it. Stunning.
T: Starkly different from the nose, but with some exquisite tastes of its own. To start, it drinks mainly like a beer of a different style, with toffee malts, hot chili pepper, toasted coconut, and a hop taste of black pepper and pine at the fore. Residual sugars, surprisingly, do little more than add a cola-like metallic twang that resonates with the spice; as such, the sweetness promised in the nose is undermined by a bright, zesty upswing you’d expect more in a winter warmer or some other heavily-spiced brew. Towards the back end are more stout-friendly flavors of toasted bourbon barrel, molasses, burnt sugar, and espresso. The finish, though, is earthy and spicy: lingering chili pepper heat on top of ashy campfire.
M: For 14% alcohol, this isn’t exactly what I expected: there’s a thinness to the body that can’t go unnoticed. In fact, it’s the worst part about this beer, and probably the only thing about it that’s keeping it from being one of the truly great stouts I’ve ever tasted – believe me, it’s that jarring.
O: Thicken the body and you’ve got a KBS killer on your hands. However, a thin texture, coupled with the thinning flavors of metal and spice, make for a flawed beer. Apart from that, though, this beer is excellent: you can tell that it was expertly crafted by brewers who have experience making quality products. Needless to say, I’m excited to see what else Prairie brings to town. 2,125 charactersBarryMFBurton, Oct 17, 2013
